Well went 2 seperate times to give them a chance as I'm a Bronx raised executive chef in Manhattan who went to le cordon bleu in France culinary school and I may know a thing or 2 about food and I live in the area. Bought a 8pc shrimp dinner and a 2pc whiting fish dinner with mac and cheese. First the orders take 20-30 mins when frying fish or shrimp takes 2-3 in a fryer. With no customers in the building and no active delivery orders with them just talking and ignoring you and your order. (I guess people in Bronx don't deserve professionalism and customer service) further I asked for mac and cheese the manager/order taker (remember this it's important) I guess was leaving at 4pm to her babies as she stated but when she walked out the other girl cooking the fish said this was off referring to the steam table all day. She pulled out a new mac and cheese put it in the steam table went into the fridge grabbed cold milk poured into the mac and cheese stirred it and scooped it into my to go container with the 2 fish dinner. When I got in the car I opened the container only to be hit with a vinegar smell of old musty fish. I brought my food back and asked for my money only for that dinner back. Which their response was we don't give refunds. They said we need to call the manager and proceed to call the order taker that just left to her babies ("the manager") only for her to explain how and when she got the fish which she said that morning which before I got on the call the 1 cooking the food said they received the fish the day before. As a chef I know first hand by experience that you can receive old and musty fish from your vendor and if you are not inspecting your product this happens. I will never return and will not support a business regardless what ethic business owner they may be that doesn't respect the Bronx community with the professionalism and proper customer service. Or at least a system in place so your business can self sustain itself when no manager or owner in the building and the business is left to teenagers to manager and control the quality of food and type of service they provide. So much potential in the right location just poor decision making by the owner herself!!!

I really wanted to like this restaurant so much. It's one of the very few soul food eateries in the Bronx and it's owned by a Black Woman. For those reasons alone it made me want to support this restaurant. After talking with a friend of mine who had previously tasted the food telling me the food was pretty decent, I figured I'd give it a try since I was in the area. The afternoon of Thursday June 27th was my first time ever visiting this establishment. Since it was ferociously hot outside, I was elated to see that the restaurant had adequate seating for us to come in from out of the heat and sit down to enjoy a meal. However, as we walked in and stood on line we realized that there was no AC, only a small floor standing fan that didn't really help to cut down on the heat coming in from outside. Still wanting to support the business and experience the restaurant we decided to stay and brave the heat. As we got to the front of the line to order, I inquired with the nice cashier as to how we could place our order since there were no paper menus available to look over and there were none posted anywhere around the restaurant. The only thing that was visible was a paper on the counter with 2 options that stated the special of the day. [The 2 large overhead TV's that hang over the counter were off, is where I'm assuming the menus would be displayed] The cashier politely told us that she could tell us what they have so we could place our order. After the cashier read us the food options off the POS screen in front of her, we placed our order, paid, sat down, and waited for our food. I ordered the 4 piece chicken wing meal with french fries, a side of mac & cheese, candied yams and a fruit punch drink. My friend ordered the same chicken dinner & drink, along with a fried catfish dinner, and a soda. The wait was a bit long but not a big deal to me because it was understandable seeing as how there were only 3 employees working: 1 was the cashier, and the other 2 were prepping and preparing the food. As we waited a little longer for our food, the friend I was with decided that she could no longer bear the heat so she wanted to take our order to go. That was fine seeing as how the next location we were going to would be sufficient to sit and enjoy our food. The cashier finally called our number and I went up to  the counter to retrieve our orders. She repeated the orders to me to verify they were correct (which I loved, because not many of the restaurants in the area take the time to confirm your order) we thanked her and left. After getting to our next destination and settling down, we were excited to taste our meals. As I opened the plastic containers, everything smelled delicious. The first thing I wanted to taste was the mac & cheese which was decent, but nothing special. Then I picked up one of my chicken wings and noticed a long black hair cooked into it. I was nauseated behind this and immediately turned off, I didn't even get to taste the rest of my food. My friend checked her food and said it looked to be fine, however at this point my appetite was ruined. I immediately packed my food back up and went right back to the restaurant for a full refund. After telling the cashier about this unfortunate situation and showing her the chicken, she did offer for my chicken to be redone but I kindly refused and she gave me a full refund with no problem. With all due respect, the girl that cooked the food was wearing a hair net and I totally understand that these situations are inevitable in any business and nothing is perfect so I'm not totally counting this establishment out. My friend said she enjoyed everything she had ordered, so I'll possibly give it another try. I wish this restaurant the best of luck and hope that it thrives for years to come. Hopefully when I return I'll have a better experience.
